ðŸ§± 5. SQL Fundamentals

âž• a. CREATE Database & Table

CREATE DATABASE StudentDB;
USE StudentDB;

CREATE TABLE Student (
    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(50),
    age INT,
    city VARCHAR(30)
);

ðŸ“¥ b. INSERT Data

INSERT INTO Student (name, age, city)
VALUES ('Tanmay', 21, 'Pune');

ðŸ“¤ c. SELECT Data

SELECT * FROM Student;             -- all columns
SELECT name, city FROM Student;    -- specific columns
SELECT * FROM Student WHERE age > 18;

âœï¸ d. UPDATE Data

UPDATE Student
SET city = 'Mumbai'
WHERE name = 'Tanmay';

ðŸ—‘ï¸ e. DELETE Data

DELETE FROM Student WHERE id = 1;


---

ðŸ”— 6. Keys and Constraints

Keys ensure uniqueness and relationships between tables.

Type	Description	Example

Primary Key (PK)	Uniquely identifies each record.	id
Foreign Key (FK)	Connects two tables.	student_id in marks table
Unique Key	No duplicates allowed.	email
Not Null	Field must have a value.	name NOT NULL
Default	Sets a default value.	status DEFAULT 'active'


Example:

CREATE TABLE Marks (
    mark_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    student_id INT,
    subject VARCHAR(50),
    marks INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (student_id) REFERENCES Student(id)
);


---

ðŸ§® 7. SQL Clauses and Operators

Clause	Description	Example

WHERE	Filter rows	WHERE age > 18
ORDER BY	Sort results	ORDER BY name DESC
GROUP BY	Group rows	GROUP BY city
HAVING	Filter grouped results	HAVING COUNT(*) > 1
LIMIT	Restrict output rows	LIMIT 5



---

ðŸ§© 8. Joins (Connecting Tables)

Used to combine data from multiple tables.

Type	Description	Example

INNER JOIN	Common rows in both tables	Student JOIN Marks
LEFT JOIN	All from left, matching from right	Student LEFT JOIN Marks
RIGHT JOIN	All from right, matching from left	â€”
FULL JOIN	All records (not in MySQL directly, but simulated)	â€”


Example:

SELECT Student.name, Marks.subject, Marks.marks
FROM Student
INNER JOIN Marks ON Student.id = Marks.student_id;


---

ðŸ”’ 9. Views, Indexes, and Stored Procedures

View

A virtual table created from query results.

CREATE VIEW TopStudents AS
SELECT name, marks FROM Marks WHERE marks > 80;

Index

Speeds up search queries.

CREATE INDEX idx_city ON Student(city);

Stored Procedure

Reusable block of SQL code.

DELIMITER //
CREATE PROCEDURE GetAllStudents()
BEGIN
    SELECT * FROM Student;
END //
DELIMITER ;
CALL GetAllStudents();


---

ðŸ§  10. Transactions & ACID Properties

Used in banking, booking systems, etc.

Example:

START TRANSACTION;
UPDATE Account SET balance = balance - 500 WHERE id = 1;
UPDATE Account SET balance = balance + 500 WHERE id = 2;
COMMIT;  -- or ROLLBACK if error

ACID Properties:

Property	Meaning

Atomicity	All or nothing
Consistency	Data remains valid
Isolation	Transactions donâ€™t interfere
Durability	Changes persist even if system fails



---

ðŸ“Š 11. Functions in MySQL

Aggregate Functions

SELECT COUNT(*), AVG(age), MAX(age), MIN(age), SUM(marks)
FROM Student;

String Functions

SELECT UPPER(name), LENGTH(city) FROM Student;

Date Functions

SELECT NOW(), YEAR(DOB), MONTH(DOB) FROM Student;


